programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.sub-title: It's all Because of the Lollipop
programme.desc: Joe Croaker finds himself a treat of a large lollipop. After gorging on it, Joe places the hollowed lollipop around his neck and starts to toy with it. Not until he tries in vain to remove the lolly does he realize that he is stuck in it. As the lolly around Joe’s neck begins to melt, it becomes sticky and attracts many leaves to it. Joe looks just like a scary monster in that leafy lollipop! The other bug buddies are all frightened at the sight of Joe, mistaking him for the ruthless monster that has swallowed Joe alive. To revenge their good friend, the folks conceive a plan to capture “the monster”. Joe is cornered into a big ditch, where the lollipop around his neck is broken apart by McBroom’s dung ball. Not until then do the folks realize that the “monster” is none other than Joe Croaker! Just when the frog is about to fly off the handle, his buddies have already made themselves scarce.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: Joe Croaker is intrigued when he sees Niddy travels with her silk. The frog believes he might be able to do the same.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.sub-title: Joe's got a Fish Bone in His Throat
programme.desc: Joe Croaker is on the prowl for food and the fish obtained by Cosmo makes his mouth water. As is typical of Joe Croaker the greedy bully frog, he snatches the fish from Cosmo and quickly swallows it whole. But such voracity only results in the bones being stuck in Joe’s throat. Seeing Joe in great pain, Cosmo is in panic and at a loss what to do to help. At that moment, Bartle Bee happens to pass by and offers Joe his nectar to help ease the pain. But it fails to work. Then Bartle suggests two possible solutions he learnt from books, which are ramming down the bones with a bun and dissolving them with vinegar. Cosmo and Joe hurry to the Garbage can and score both a bun and a bottle of vinegar, but it turns out neither way helps remove the bones from Joe’s throat. In the end, proposed again by the resourceful Bartle Bee, they hang Joe Croaker upside down and succeed in swinging the bones out of Joe’s throat.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: Fed up living in his shabby can house, Cosmo decides to find himself a sleek, cozy new place. First he is taken with the fancy-looking paper box with pretty patterns and good light, but Bartle Bee reminds him of its vulnerability to rain in wet seasons. So he keeps on searching his dream home. Then, a crystal clear glass jar commands Cosmo’s attention. Just when he is about to make it his new abode, the mole cricket’s warning against this heat-accumulating material discourages him from settling down there. So Cosmo has to look for other alternatives. Then he discovers a large magnet which he uses to attract pieces of parts together and make them into a solidly constructed iron house. After a long day’s rushing about, Cosmo retires to rest at his pleasant new home. But something bad happens. A coin is drawn to the magnet house and blocks the exit. Trapped inside his own house, Cosmo shouts for help, which invites Joe Croaker over. The frog agrees to help him out on the condition that Cosmo offers him both service and food. But instead of getting Cosmo out, Joe accidentally sets a large iron lid running, which crashes into the magnet house. Luckily enough, Cosmo is able to survive with the help of the mole cricket. In the end, Joe Croaker has to compensate Cosmo by offering him his service instead.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: Cosmo has got a nice ice cream postage stamp, which is overheard by Joe Croaker. The thought of the tasty ice cream tempts the amphibian into a plot to steal the stamp from Cosmo. He tails Cosmo, and tries in vain to grab the stamp. Tired from the flight, Cosmo rests himself upon a branch, covering himself with the stamp. Seeing this as a good opportunity, Joe employs every possible method known to him to try to score the stamp. But none of them really works. Then the green vines hanging down the tree inspire him. He uses the vines to climb up and reaches out for the stamp. He then falls off onto the ground along with the stamp. Just when Joe assumes he has secured the ice cream stamp for good, a gust of wind blows it up to the tree again. Cosmo wakes up and joyfully takes the stamp back home.

programme.title: Masters of the Zodiac
programme.desc: Briar and Tiki chases their kite to Old Billy’s vegetable patch, and accidentally trample the vegetables. Although they try to correct the deed, but it just get worse. They try to avoid Old Billy in school and hesitate to apologize to him, for fear Old Billy will be angry. Briar tries to get Tiki and apologize to Old Billy. The old man tells them he’s going to the vegetable field to grow new vegetables. Briar and Tiki help him out. At last, they tell Old Billy the truth. The old man doesn’t get angry. Instead, he thinks they are responsible kids.

programme.title: Masters of the Zodiac
programme.desc: Luna-Loo doesn’t want to keep her old or broken toys, and asks her parents to buy her new ones. So she secretly throws away her old toys. When she visits Violet’s home, however, she finds out her friends treasure her toys very much, and remembers the good times she has spent with her toys. Then it rains. Luna-Loo quickly goes outside to find her toys with Violet but can’t find them. She’s feels regret. The next morning, she’s surprised to find out that all her toys are back. It turns out her mom picks up those toys, cleans and mends them. Luna-Loo realizes her mistake and thanks her mom. Violet and Vick come to Luna-Loo’s home and help her modify some old toys. Everyone is happy.

programme.title: Masters of the Zodiac
programme.sub-title: Summoning the Sun & The Frog Friends
programme.desc: Luna-Loo stays at Violet’s home for the night. They borrow a toy car from Vick powered by solar energy. However, the car runs out of power at night. They are disappointed to find out the sun has already set. They decide to summon the sun. First they to use some “magic spells”, then an ice cream to “entice” the sun to come out. They even mimic the sound of roosters to try to call for the sun. The sun never comes out. Instead, Violet’s parents are woken by the noise. Through a little experiment, they explain to the kids about solar rotation and the switch of night and day.

programme.title: Masters of the Zodiac
programme.desc: Briar and Bramble discover that Old Billy’s office smells bad. They decide to help him get rid of the awful smell. They try to collect some fresh clean air from a flower field with bottles, and bring the air to the office. However, it’s hard to tell whether the fragrance is really inside the bottles. So they decide to use balloons to collect the scent. However, a little hedgehog accidentally pops the balloons when he tries to help them. Old Billy sees them and tells them that the stinky smell will go away if they keep good ventilation in the office.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: Briar has a toothache and Vick tells him there are bugs eating his teeth, making him anxious. To get the bugs out, they try many methods, such as gargling water, asking Hoo Hoo to peck the bugs out, and singing to lure the bugs out, all of which are proven to be useless. At last, they go to see Nurse Beakman, then they find out the cause of tooth decay, and learn how to protect their teeth.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: Violet has a treasure chest, inside which Luna-Loo likes the moon stone the most. That day, Luna-Loo hides the treasure chest somewhere else without Violet’s permission, but what she doesn’t know is that Ms. Lady Jane witnesses the whole thing. The cubs are busy helping Violet look for the chest, while Luna-Loo is invited to Ms. Lady Jane’s office, where she hears Violet’s words about how she cherishes the chest. Luna-Loo realizes what she has done is not right. Ms. Lady Jane comes in. She asks Luna-Loo to return a screwdriver to Vick, and tells her that even though she likes the screwdriver, she can’t keep it because she’s not the owner. Luna-Loo puts the chest back and makes a confession to her friends.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.sub-title: The Family Visit & You Get What You Put In
programme.desc: Little Briar misbehaves at kindergarten and refuses to apologize to the other kids. Ms. Olivia happens to go to the kids’ home for family visits. Briar is afraid that mom will learn about his behavior at kindergarten, so he tries various means to stop the family visit. Despite of this, Ms. Olivia still meets Briar’s mom. Seeing he could do nothing to stop the family visit, Briar tells the truth. Ms. Olivia tells Briar that he needs to confront his problems, and Briar learns a valuable lesson.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.sub-title: Tiki the Weatherman & Herby’s Helpful Apples
programme.desc: Old Billy forecasts the weather right, and Tiki asks Old Billy to teach him how to forecast a rainy day. Tiki makes notes and memorizes it. The other kids at Pine Tree Kindergarten plan to have a picnic, and Tiki tells them the weather will be sunny. However, just when the kids are going to have the picnic, it rains. Tiki goes to find Old Billy and asks him what’s wrong with the weather forecast. Old Billy explains that nature changes constantly and that only by studying hard could they make weather forecasts as accurate as possible.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.sub-title: Kitty the Tiger & The Magic Words
programme.desc: An uninvited guest, Kitty the tiger, sneaks into the drawing class, and shocks the whole class. But later this adorable tiger wins everybody’s heart. They like her, and volunteer to look after her. Kitty makes much trouble. However to make her happy, Prince Tiki lets her have his favorite bag. During naptime, kitty misses her mom so much that she can’t stop crying. Then the kids sing for her to help her sleep. It’s time to say goodbye. Everybody feels sad to part with her. Ms. Olivia promises that Kitty will attend the kindergarten when she grows up, making them happy again.

programme.title: Origins Of The Twelve
programme.desc: Fierce begs Guardian to teach him martial arts, and Guardian lies to him that the secret of success is smile. Fierce takes his words seriously and keeps smiling all day, which scares his companions away. The martial arts competition kicks off on the next day. Fierce jumps onto the arena first and Poppy follows to take up the challenge. Just as the master predicted, Poppy knocks out Fierce with the slightest effort.

programme.title: Origins Of The Twelve
programme.desc: Guardian keeps bragging about his glorious past and Fierce gets tired of his jawing away. Fierce plucks some wild fruits from a tree to eat, which makes him suffer from diarrhea. They take a short break and continue the journey. Several hours later, Fierce finds that he has passed the same fruit tree he met just now for three times and they are walking around in a circle. But Guardian doesn’t listen to him and moves on.

programme.title: Origins Of The Twelve
programme.desc: Fierce and Guardian thank Cloud Hand for his delicious food and prepare to start off. Cloud Hand tells them they can stay overnight at his house because there are many bumpy roads nearby and they may get lost easily. Guardian refuses his invitation politely and draws Fierce away. But soon after, they cannot find their way and come back again. Cloud Hand makes up a guest room for them and says he’ll show them the way out of the forest the next morning.

programme.title: Origins Of The Twelve
programme.desc: Cloud Hand is hung upside down on a tree with his feet tied. The branch breaks off and he drops onto the ground. Guardian says Cloud Hand must have been sleepwalking at night and tied himself to the tree. Cloud Hand falls for what he says and doesn’t feel angry at all. Guardian says the pig must have pretended to be so nice and they need to test his character. They throw a coin, an ingot of silver, and an ingot of gold onto the ground on purpose, only to find that Cloud Hand is not interested in them at all and just cares about his food materials. They put off their doubts completely and begin to enjoy the dishes Cloud Hand cooks.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: The cubs break the trophy they won at the sports meeting. Fear of being criticized by Ms. Oliva, they make up a story that a blue bird attacks Briar and accidentally breaks the trophy. Ms. Olivia sees through their lie and gives them a lesson on honesty. The cubs confess their fault, and fix the trophy together.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: Bramble decides to keep the caterpillar he finds on his head, and see how it grows up and becomes a butterfly. As time goes by, the caterpillar becomes a pupa, and soon it will turn into a butterfly. But in the process of metamorphosis, Bramble worries that it might get stuck, and tries to help. Ms. Olivia stops him and tells him that it needs to do it itself to get enough strength to fly. Just as they expected, the butterfly finally comes out, dries its wings, and flies.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: The kids at Pine Tree Kindergarten are discussing what they want to be when they grow up. Vick says he wants to be an inventor and boasts that it’s easy to invent. To prove his point, he wants to invent something to dig holes as well as something for him to fly. However, both inventions meet with failure. Just when he is discouraged, he sees little Briar and Tiki playing paper planes. They are having a little contest. Then Vick gets an idea when he sees Bramble’s balloon. He attaches the balloon to the paper plane, and invents a “balloon plane” which could fly the most distance.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: The cubs have got a new classmate – Ernie Jo, whose ears look different. A rumor starts that Ernie Jo’s big ears are infectious. Everybody tries to avoid him until Babu touches one of his ear by accident and he’s totally fine. The rumor is cleared and the cubs accept him. They invite Ernie Jo to play hide and seek. With the help of his big ears, Ernie Jo leads the cubs to find Little Vick who has fallen asleep and snores during the game. Now everybody wishes to have big ears like Ernie Jo’s do.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.sub-title: Rainy Day Fun & The More, The Better?
programme.desc: Violet hates rainy days. She doesn’t get why the others are having fun as usual. She tries to practice her flute, but rain drops cause her flute to get out of tune. Violet gets quite embarrassed and bursts into tears. To comfort her, everybody else gets busy doing funny tricks. Violet stops crying, asks why they enjoy the rain, and finds her own fun on rainy days.

In the end, Joe Croaker has to compensate Cosmo by offering him his service instead.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: Cosmo has got a nice ice cream postage stamp, which is overheard by Joe Croaker. The thought of the tasty ice cream tempts the amphibian into a plot to steal the stamp from Cosmo. He tails Cosmo, and tries in vain to grab the stamp. Tired from the flight, Cosmo rests himself upon a branch, covering himself with the stamp. Seeing this as a good opportunity, Joe employs every possible method known to him to try to score the stamp. But none of them really works. Then the green vines hanging down the tree inspire him. He uses the vines to climb up and reaches out for the stamp. He then falls off onto the ground along with the stamp. Just when Joe assumes he has secured the ice cream stamp for good, a gust of wind blows it up to the tree again. Cosmo wakes up and joyfully takes the stamp back home.

programme.title: Masters of the Zodiac
programme.desc: Briar and Tiki chases their kite to Old Billy’s vegetable patch, and accidentally trample the vegetables. Although they try to correct the deed, but it just get worse. They try to avoid Old Billy in school and hesitate to apologize to him, for fear Old Billy will be angry. Briar tries to get Tiki and apologize to Old Billy. The old man tells them he’s going to the vegetable field to grow new vegetables. Briar and Tiki help him out. At last, they tell Old Billy the truth. The old man doesn’t get angry. Instead, he thinks they are responsible kids.

programme.title: Masters of the Zodiac
programme.desc: Luna-Loo doesn’t want to keep her old or broken toys, and asks her parents to buy her new ones. So she secretly throws away her old toys. When she visits Violet’s home, however, she finds out her friends treasure her toys very much, and remembers the good times she has spent with her toys. Then it rains. Luna-Loo quickly goes outside to find her toys with Violet but can’t find them. She’s feels regret. The next morning, she’s surprised to find out that all her toys are back. It turns out her mom picks up those toys, cleans and mends them. Luna-Loo realizes her mistake and thanks her mom. Violet and Vick come to Luna-Loo’s home and help her modify some old toys. Everyone is happy.

programme.title: Masters of the Zodiac
programme.sub-title: Summoning the Sun & The Frog Friends
programme.desc: Luna-Loo stays at Violet’s home for the night. They borrow a toy car from Vick powered by solar energy. However, the car runs out of power at night. They are disappointed to find out the sun has already set. They decide to summon the sun. First they to use some “magic spells”, then an ice cream to “entice” the sun to come out. They even mimic the sound of roosters to try to call for the sun. The sun never comes out. Instead, Violet’s parents are woken by the noise. Through a little experiment, they explain to the kids about solar rotation and the switch of night and day.

programme.title: Masters of the Zodiac
programme.desc: Briar and Bramble discover that Old Billy’s office smells bad. They decide to help him get rid of the awful smell. They try to collect some fresh clean air from a flower field with bottles, and bring the air to the office. However, it’s hard to tell whether the fragrance is really inside the bottles. So they decide to use balloons to collect the scent. However, a little hedgehog accidentally pops the balloons when he tries to help them. Old Billy sees them and tells them that the stinky smell will go away if they keep good ventilation in the office.

programme.title: Pondemonium
programme.desc: Briar has a toothache and Vick tells him there are bugs eating his teeth, making him anxious. To get the bugs out, they try many methods, such as gargling water, asking Hoo Hoo to peck the bugs out, and singing to lure the bugs out, all of which are proven to be useless. At last, they go to see Nurse Beakman, then they find out the cause of tooth decay, and learn how to protect their teeth.

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: A vague tip leads Matt and Dale into a WWII era military warehouse and beyond.

programme.desc: A cross-country race to lay claim to some of the world’s most sought after works specials.

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: “12hrs. & Running”: Dale turns a surprise 60th birthday party into a challenge to his guests to start 120 of the rarest motorcycles in the world.

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: An family farm in the mid-west contains houses, barns, outbuildings, trailers, grain silos and buses full of old stuff and perhaps the biggest stash of undiscovered old motorcycles in the country. The collection was put together by their unnamed father. Seller agrees to have Dale broker rare Excelsior for high-end client. Dale has the buyer, but will he outbid his own client for the exclusive find?

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: Matt is out for revenge. Last year Dale beat him badly at the Annual Vintage bike race in Barber, Alabama. But this year there is a whole new tale to tell. With just days until the race - Dale is secretly struggling to get the bike he beat Matt with last year up and working. Matt struggles just to locate a 100-year old bike. Matt's prayers are answered thanks to an old Catholic Priest he located who has possession of a bike. The priest might let Matt have the bike to race - but there are conditions. The toughest one: Don't tell Dale you have it. Can Matt afford to buy the bike and get it running in time for the race without Dale seeing it? Will Dale even get his broken bike started? And if they ever get to race, will Matt exact his revenge?

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: Built in the mid-60’s by eccentric engineer “Wild Bill” Gelbke, the Road Dog was, and still is, the largest motorcycle ever built. It utilized aircraft tubing, Corvette disc brakes, and a Chevy truck differential to keep it stable. The one-off creation disappeared when Gelbke did in 1978. Outflanked once when the bike was spotted and sold to a private collector in 1995, Dale has vowed to locate the machine and make Wheels Through Time its final resting place.

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: Big Time Motorcycle Auction

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: The RM Auction Company has worked with Dale before as a buyer, seller, historian, and caretaker at the prestigious Lee Hartung auction. But this event is no last minute rush to define one man’s treasures. This is a well calculated, time consuming, multi-media, and multi motorcycle and prized art deal.

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: Home Depot Senior Vice President, Gordon Erickson, is a huge fan of Wheels Through Time. He is also a huge supporter of the Wounded Warrior program. For years the hardware giant has been donating goods and services to help returning servicemen with their fix-it-up projects. Now they would like to go one step further and build a WWII military bike to raise awareness and funds. Only problem is where to get one? Enter Dale and an exhaustive, time sensitive, cross country search for a rare military machine.

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.desc: Promoters of the prestigious Amelia Island Concours have called on Dale to develop a show and field bikes for an “Orphan Bike” show. They have defined orphan bike as extremely rare, that aren't a Harley nor Indian machines.

programme.title: What's In the Barn?
programme.sub-title: Time is Not On Their Side
programme.desc: For Dale and Matt sometimes the dotted line to treasure splits and heads in opposite directions. In this edition of What’s in the Barn, time is thrust to the forefront of this multi-state, long distance, north, south search. Timeless and priceless 110 year old bikes, antique cars, airplanes, and the infamous Egberts 1930 neon Harley-Davidson sign that coined the phrase “Ride a Winner” are high on this father and son’s list of “must haves”. The clock ticks, both literally and figuratively, on one rare time piece and two old-timer’s cars, bikes, and automobiles.

programme.title: Truck U
programme.desc: Matt heads out west to find out what makes the King of the Hammers one of the fastest growing races in the world.

programme.title: Truck U

programme.title: Truck U
programme.desc: The Chassis for the Rock Racer is almost done, so Matt and Bruno add a Speedwire System and install the torque converter.

programme.title: Truck U

programme.title: Rutter's Detailin Garage
programme.desc: Nick Rutter walks you through step-by-step on how to remove stubborn bug splatter from your vehicle along with tips and techniques for using a waterless wash as well as a clay bar.

programme.title: Rutter's Detailin Garage
programme.desc: Nick Rutter provides tips and techniques for restoring dull, faded paint using a forced-rotation dual action polisher along with a graphene 3-in-1 ceramic polish, along with severe scratch and scuff removal.

programme.title: Caffeine & Octane
programme.desc: Daimlers and Morgans, and Citroens, oh my! Caffeine & Octane is known for having something for everyone. That reputation grows stronger as Bob Boston’s collection, on the lunatic fringe of automotive, rattles into an event; guest host Katherine Legge explains the competitor to her racing sponsor Acura, Porsche.

programme.title: Caffeine & Octane
programme.desc: Former Jet Ski Champion Ryan Hardwick has succeeded in everything he’s touched in racing and business, so why not race Lamborghinis! Hardwick has found rapid success with his high tech training methods; he shares his secrets with host Rickey Gadson in this episode of C&O.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: The premiere episode features a dive into the influence cars had on culture of California. From road racing in the 1940’s to the inception of the iconic Woody wagon on the California beach scene, automobiles undoubtedly shaped the West Coast attitude. Ray talks to The Beach Boys frontman Mike Love and surfing icon Laird Hamilton for a glimpse into the cars that are so connected to surfing culture.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: Ray uncovers the secrets of America’s greatest racing sport in the foothills of North Carolina. When moonshiners were looking to outrun police officers, they would custom fit engines to race the back woods tracks. That sport eventually evolved into NASCAR and Ray talks to the early adopters of this national pastime.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: Grammy-winning musician Marty Robbins lived a double life, flawlessly crossing between the glitz of the Grand Ole Opry and track at Talladega. One of few musicians to ever achieve success in both genres, Ray is determined to return Marty’s iconic 777 car to the race track travel back to the 60’s and 70’s.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: Legendary drag racer Don “The Snake” Prudhomme proves he is no stranger to the thrill of racing rivalry. Prudhomme’s career and subsequent competition with driver Tom “The Mongoose” McEwan earned the pair an unforgettable imprint on American pop culture. Legions of kids in the 60’s and 70’s flocked to the shelves for Snake and Mongoose Matchbox cars which helped make drag racing an undisputable American pastime. Famed director Ron Howard makes an appearance to discuss the incredible stories hidden within the world of Formula 1 Racing, the topic of his latest, epic feature ‘Rush”.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: Ray finds Buried Treasures in the form of two race cars that had been left almost completely untouched since the last time they were on a race track. One is found sitting in a barn with the other trapped in an old car hauler. Upon uncovering the cars, we find both have big stories to tell.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: A journey to Indianapolis unveils the winning car of the 1955 Indy 500 sits on the roof of an auto mechanic shop. More than 50 years after it’s magic at the track, prominent Indy mechanic/owner Chris Paulsen begins to restore the car and Ray talks about the evolution of America’s illustrious Indy 500.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: In the 1960s, Smokey Yunick, the most innovative mechanic in NASCAR history, sold his famous truck that hauled equipment & cars across the country. Ray is on a mission to uncover this storied truck that helped launch the beginning of NASCAR’s cross-country popularity.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: Ray travels to Long Island, New York with the hopes of learning more about America’s first major auto racing competition. The race, which began at the turn of the 20th century, helped develop the first major American racing stars and drove American manufacturing to competitive standard with the highly progressive Europeans.

programme.title: Caffeine & Octane
programme.desc: Call the Peach State Challengers a “car club” and you will quickly be corrected. The defenders of everything Dodge are “family” and they make no excuses for their loyalty to brand and brother. Spend a day at the track with these Challengers and find out what their version of the family photo looks like.

programme.title: Caffeine & Octane
programme.desc: Imagination, ingenuity, and heartache join friends who set out with a simple goal of transforming a ‘35 Plymouth into a running taxi cab. Provenance and passion take center stage as families and friends strive for best in show. Host Rickey Gadson checks out perfect replicas of the original Shelby Cobras and takes Skip and Bryan on ‘borrowed’ taxi ride.

programme.title: Caffeine & Octane
programme.desc: The natural landscape of Jekyll Island, GA makes for a great backdrop to showcase the country’s greatest cars. But the ocean air and remoteness of this GA barrier island is no place to leave a painstakingly rebuilt ‘59 Imperial Speedster. Host Skip Smith makes it his mission to locate the talented builder behind this island mystery. Guest host Totem joins Bryan Fuller in the C&O lots to pick out his favorites.

programme.title: Caffeine & Octane
programme.desc: The word is out that Caffeine & Octane is the major league of North American car shows. Former Atlanta Brave, World Series star, and 10-Time Gold Glove winner Andruw Jones acknowledged the stardom and showed up to show off his 6 wheeled Super Jeep. The state of the art creation took years in planning and execution, but Jones chooses one great event for its debut.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: Fred Dmuchowski is a New Jersey racing icon. He was a regular workingman who raced on weekends for fun and became a legend in his iconic 303 racer. Ray works to rebuild the 303 in homage to Fred who inspired him to pursue his career in motorsports.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: For Rick Hendrick, the Corvette inspired his first car purchase, which ultimately led to the creation of his car dealership empire and motorsports teams. Mr. H, as he goes by, gives us a rare look inside of his personal Corvette collection and takes us to General Motors World Headquarters to talk with GM Vice President of Global Design, Ed Welburn, about how this iconic car came about. Country superstar Brad Paisley makes a cameo appearance to talk about his prized ‘Vette and the influence of cars on his music.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: The last car Elvis drove the evening he passed was his beloved Stutz Blackhawk. Ray discovers that the car has been preserved and heads to Graceland to check out this iconic piece of American music history. Ray and the team reveal the impeccable preservation of the car at Charlotte Motor Speedway with Rick Hendrick (“Mr. H”) and, arguably Elvis Presley’s biggest fan, Dale Earnhardt Jr. While at Graceland, Ray and the team also get an exclusive look at the paneled station wagon Elvis used to get in and out of Graceland in disguise. It’s an intimate look at the King’s incredible automobiles and their secrets that only Elvis knew.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: This episode takes an inside look at the famous racing L88 Corvette. From its history, to its successes and heartbreaks, to the stories of the men that drove it. Now, it’s a car world’s version of the Flinstones meet the Jetsons, as the Owens Corning Corvette, which clinched 22 straight race victories, challenges the new Corvette C7-R at Sebring International Raceway. The original Owens Corning team reunites for the challenge and our crew goes behind the scenes for the Corvette test drive of a lifetime.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: From break up to make up, Jeff Gordon and Ray reunite to go on a quest to find their Chevrolet Monte Carlo that claimed victory in their final race together at Phoenix, AZ in 1999. John Bickford, Jeff Gordon’s stepdad, makes the call that reunites the old team. Jeff and Ray look to bum parts off their boss, Rick Hendrick, to make their vision a reality: get the car, replace the parts as they were, make it run and get it to auction.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: One of the greatest battles in NASCAR history was Hall of Famer Richie Evans and rival speedster Jerry Cook. Ray is determined to uncover and revive the cars that made these men famous.Ray purchases one of Richie’s original #61 modifieds from Jimmy Spencer and restores it to its original glory while simultaneously building a replica of Jerry Cook’s #38. Throughout the build process, Ray uncovers stories about these legends through the eyes of guys who were in Rome, NY to witness it firsthand, like Robin Pemberton and Steve Hmiel.Both cars will hit the track at Martinsville, site of one of the greatest races in modified history and the tragic death of Richie Evans himself. Legends live again, as Ray recreates one of the racing world’s most celebrated rivalries on a track that has seen it all.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: General Motors VP of global design Ed Welburn takes AmeriCarna behind the scenes to talk about the history and development of the company’s concept cars that never made it to production. In a rare tour of the factory’s inner design studio, Ray gets an exclusive look behind the creative curtain at the GM plant in Detroit.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: In this episode, Ray celebrates the 50th birthday of the Ford Mustang through the lens of three distinct Mustang owners, who each hold a slice of the car’s incredible history. In 1964, Chicago schoolteacher Gail Wise unknowingly purchased the first ever Mustang 3 days before the car became available to the general public. Her husband reveals the incredible restoration that brought the earliest Mustang ever sold back to its 60’s glory. (Ford Motor Company knows she has the car and has verified it was sold before it was legal to sell.) John Grafelman is a farmer in Illinois and life-long Ford lover. A few years ago he found an old car hidden in a barn. It took some time, but he eventually convinced his friend to sell it to him. After some detective work, he discovers he purchased 1968 Ford Design Chief Larry Shinoda’s personal car that he tinkered with to invent the BOSS 302.Lastly, Ray travels to Dayton Ohio to interview Gale Holderman, the Ford stylist who won the company’s contest to draw and design the Mustang.

programme.title: AmeriCarna
programme.desc: Post-World War II, a large generation of American soldiers was looking for cars that mirrored the incredible sports cars they saw overseas in Europe. After searching for an affordable way to recreate these cars, one manufacturer responded with a durable, cost effective option: a line of fiberglass sports cars. Very few of these cars still exist but there are collectors who are constantly looking to save parts and pieces of these virtually unknown vehicles. We learn about these rare cars from Geoff Hacker and his team at Forgotten Fiberglass, and take a visit to the Smithsonian Museum, which houses a fiberglass car of its own. This episode presents a unique look at how the narrative of American wartime experiences often shaped the nation’s automotive demands.
